 rhetorical plot involving narratives that treat the churches as objects of desire. Drawing on the testimony of three witnesses involved in church building—Abbot Suger of Saint-Denis, Gervase of Canterbury, and the image maker Villard de Honnecourt—and a range of secondary sources, Murray traces common patterns in the way medieval buildings were represented in words and images. Our witnesses provide vital information about the way the great churches of Gothic were built and the complexity of their meanings. Taking a fresh approach to Gothic architecture, Plotting Gothic offers an invigorating new way to understand some of the most lasting achievements of the medieval era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArchitecture, GothicxSocial aspects. 0aArchitecture, Gothic. 70(DE-601)1042803520(DE-588)4002851-3aArchitektur2gnd 70(DE-601)1047321640(DE-588)4021656-1aGotik2gnd 70(DE-601)1047912680(DE-588)4073436-5aKirchenbau2gnd 70(DE-601)1058361090(DE-588)4112587-3aArchitekturtheorie2gnd 7aARCHITECTURE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022619180540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226191942423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226191942/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles